        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Jan 21 1874</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am very glad to hear of a new ed. of the Descent of Man, but it will be impossible for you to have corrected sheets for some time.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I have revised the style largely, &amp; have altered &amp; added to many parts. I hope that it will be considerably improved. I shall have it stereotyped so that it will never be corrected again.</p>
<p>As far as I can judge, the sheets will not be ready for the printer for 6 or 8 weeks; &amp; then there will be the correcting the proofs &amp; printing off the sheets. There will be a few new woodcuts. As far as I can see (which is blindly) it will not be possible to send you corrected sheets for about 3 months.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>At present my work of revision is stopped for a week or 2 by a new edition of my small book on Coral Reefs   I think perhaps this book w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> sell in Germany if translated; &amp; if Mess<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Smith &amp; Elder w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> supply stereotype plates at a moderate profit to them.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>I am extremely glad to hear a pretty good account of your health; &amp; that Edinburgh suited you so well.<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>When you come to England I hope that you will be able to pay me a visit.</p>
<p>Out of curiosity &amp; vanity I should like to hear (some time) how many copies have been sold in Germany, of <hi rend="underline">my Descent</hi> of man, <hi rend="underline">Expression</hi> &amp; <hi rend="underline">other books</hi>.<ref target="#foot.f5"/></p>
<p>My dear Sir | yours very sincerely. | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">2.3 (which is blindly)] <hi rend="italic">parentheses over commas, in CD’s hand</hi> </note>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9248.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. V. Carus, 19 January 1874</ref> and n. 1. CD was preparing a new edition of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD sent the first part of the new edition of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> to the printers in March 1874 and received the first proofs in May (see letters to J. V. Carus, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9340.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">8 March [1874]</ref>, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9464.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">23 May [1874]</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD was preparing a new edition of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1571.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Coral reefs</hi></ref>, published by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4407.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Smith, Elder &amp; Co</ref>. (see letter to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4407.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Smith, Elder &amp; Co</ref>, 8 January 1874). Carus translated <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1571.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Coral reefs</hi></ref> in 1876 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1300.xml">Carus trans. 1876</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Carus suffered from frequent bronchial complaints, but his condition had improved in the summer of 1873, when he was teaching in Edinburgh (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9248.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. V. Carus, 19 January 1874</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">Carus sent the sales figures with his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9363.xml">letter of 15 March 1874</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
